1
00:03:07,753 --> 00:03:11,945
This is what I get in return for 30 years
of service for my company?

2
00:03:12,031 --> 00:03:14,959
And they send some yo-yo like you
in here,

3
00:03:15,045 --> 00:03:17,464
to try to tell me that I'm out of a job?

4
00:03:17,550 --> 00:03:19,800
They should be telling you
you're out of a job.

5
00:03:19,886 --> 00:03:23,810
You have a lot of gall, coming in here
and firing your No.1 producer.

6
00:03:23,896 --> 00:03:27,188
You're going to go home and make
more money than you've ever made in your life

7
00:03:27,274 --> 00:03:29,542
and I'm going to go home
without a pay cheque. Fuck you.

8
00:03:29,628 --> 00:03:33,634
I guess you leave me dumbfounded.
I don't know where this is coming from.

9
00:03:33,720 --> 00:03:38,026
How am I meant to go back as a man
and explain to my wife I lost my job?

10
00:03:38,112 --> 00:03:44,440
On a stress level, I've heard that
losing your job is like a death in the family.

11
00:03:44,763 --> 00:03:48,920
But personally,
I feel more like

12
00:03:49,019 --> 00:03:53,352
the people I worked with
were my family and I died.

13
00:03:53,438 --> 00:03:55,912
I can't afford to be unemployed.

14
00:03:55,998 --> 00:03:58,780
I have a house payment,
I have children.

15
00:03:58,866 --> 00:04:01,172
I don't know how you can live
with yourself,

16
00:04:01,258 --> 00:04:04,716
but I'm sure that you'll find a way
while the rest of us are suffering.

17
00:04:04,802 --> 00:04:07,320
Who the fuck are you, man?

18
00:04:08,051 --> 00:04:11,121
<i>Excellent question. Who the fuck am I?</i>

19
00:04:11,207 --> 00:04:13,458
<i>Poor Steve has worked here
for seven years.</i>

20
00:04:13,544 --> 00:04:17,753
<i>He's never had a meeting with me
before or passed me in the hall,</i>

21
00:04:17,839 --> 00:04:19,976
<i>or told me a story in the break room.</i>

22
00:04:20,062 --> 00:04:21,558
<i>That's because I don't work here.</i>

23
00:04:21,644 --> 00:04:24,952
<i>I work for another company that lends
me out to pussies like Steve's boss</i>

24
00:04:25,038 --> 00:04:27,504
<i>who don't have the balls
to sack their own employees,</i>

25
00:04:27,590 --> 00:04:32,810
<i>in some cases for good reason.
People do crazy shit when they get fired.</i>

26
00:04:37,117 --> 00:04:39,061
Did I do something wrong?

27
00:04:39,147 --> 00:04:41,478
I mean, is there something
I could do differently here?

28
00:04:41,564 --> 00:04:46,866
This is not an assessment of your
productivity. Don't take this personally.

29
00:04:47,201 --> 00:04:48,896
Don't take it personally.

30
00:04:48,982 --> 00:04:51,757
Steven, I want you to review this packet.

31
00:04:51,843 --> 00:04:55,660
Take it seriously. I think you're gonna
find a lot of good answers in here.

32
00:04:55,746 --> 00:04:58,084
I'm sure this is gonna be very helpful -
a packet.

33
00:04:58,170 --> 00:05:01,750
Thank you... A packet.

34
00:05:04,187 --> 00:05:09,799
Well, anybody who ever built an empire
or changed the world sat where you are right now.

35
00:05:09,885 --> 00:05:13,165
And it's because they sat there
they were able to do it.

36
00:05:13,251 --> 00:05:15,406
That's the truth.

37
00:05:21,109 --> 00:05:23,578
I'm gonna need your keycard.

38
00:05:25,477 --> 00:05:26,912
Great. OK.

39
00:05:26,998 --> 00:05:32,159
Now, I want you to take the day, go get
together your personal things, then tomorrow

40
00:05:32,245 --> 00:05:35,394
you get yourself some exercise.
You go out for a jog,

41
00:05:35,480 --> 00:05:39,774
you give yourself some routines
and pretty soon you find your legs.

42
00:05:40,273 --> 00:05:43,844
How do I get in touch with you?
- Don't worry, we'll be in touch soon.

43
00:05:43,930 --> 00:05:46,526
This is just the beginning.

44
00:05:47,087 --> 00:05:49,728
<i>I'll never see Steve again.</i>

45
00:06:08,873 --> 00:06:12,886
<i>To know me is to fly with me.
This is where I live.</i>

46
00:06:15,833 --> 00:06:16,954
<i>When I run my card,</i>

47
00:06:17,040 --> 00:06:21,876
<i>the system automatically prompts the desk clerk
to greet me with this exact statement:</i>

48
00:06:22,059 --> 00:06:23,752
Pleasure to see you again,
Mr Bingham.

49
00:06:23,838 --> 00:06:28,282
<i>It's these kinds of systemised friendly
touches that keep my world in orbit.</i>

50
00:07:03,397 --> 00:07:05,752
<i>All the things you probably hate
about travelling -</i>

51
00:07:05,838 --> 00:07:09,828
<i>the recycled air, the artificial lighting,
the digital juice dispensers,</i>

52
00:07:09,914 --> 00:07:14,646
<i>the cheap sushi -
are warm reminders that I'm home.</i>

53
00:07:27,095 --> 00:07:29,428
Do you want the cancer?

54
00:07:31,463 --> 00:07:34,058
The what?
- Do you want the cancer?

55
00:07:34,144 --> 00:07:36,058
The cancer?

56
00:07:36,205 --> 00:07:42,086
The can...sir?
- Oh, no. I'm fine, thank you.

57
00:08:03,440 --> 00:08:06,420
How much does your life weigh?

58
00:08:07,363 --> 00:08:10,158
Imagine for a second
that you're carrying a backpack.

59
00:08:10,244 --> 00:08:15,672
I want you to feel the straps
on your shoulders. Feel 'em?

60
00:08:15,995 --> 00:08:19,444
Now I want you to pack it with
all the stuff that you have in your life.

61
00:08:19,530 --> 00:08:21,292
Start with the little things,

62
00:08:21,378 --> 00:08:25,723
the things on shelves and in drawers
the knick-knacks, the collectibles.

63
00:08:25,809 --> 00:08:28,141
Feel the weight as that adds up.

64
00:08:28,227 --> 00:08:34,534
Then you start adding larger stuff -
clothes, table-top appliances, lamps, linens...

65
00:08:34,620 --> 00:08:36,728
your TV...

66
00:08:36,814 --> 00:08:40,444
The backpack should be getting
pretty heavy now. And you go bigger.

67
00:08:40,889 --> 00:08:44,708
Your couch, bed, your kitchen table.
Stuff it all in there.

68
00:08:44,794 --> 00:08:46,841
Your car, get it in there.

69
00:08:46,927 --> 00:08:51,338
Your home, whether it's
a studio apartment or a two-bedroomed house.

70
00:08:51,424 --> 00:08:55,542
I want you to stuff it all
into that backpack.

71
00:08:56,761 --> 00:08:59,134
Now try to walk.

72
00:09:00,529 --> 00:09:02,934
It's kind of hard, isn't it?

73
00:09:03,137 --> 00:09:05,094
This is what we do to ourselves
on a daily basis

74
00:09:05,180 --> 00:09:09,993
We weigh ourselves down until we can't
even move. And make no mistake...

75
00:09:10,079 --> 00:09:11,957
moving is living.

76
00:09:12,043 --> 00:09:16,340
Now, I'm gonna set that backpack on fire.
What do you want to take out of it?

77
00:09:16,426 --> 00:09:18,111
Photos?

78
00:09:18,197 --> 00:09:22,874
Photos are for people who can't remember.
Drink some ginkgo and let the photos burn.

79
00:09:23,177 --> 00:09:29,631
In fact, let everything burn
and imagine waking up tomorrow with nothing.

80
00:09:30,721 --> 00:09:33,660
It's kind of exhilarating, isn't it?

81
00:09:40,424 --> 00:09:42,996
Welcome back, Mr Bingham.

82
00:09:51,891 --> 00:09:55,636
Ryan Bingham's office.
- You have me in a Dodge Stratus in Kansas City.

83
00:09:55,722 --> 00:09:58,283
They were out of all full-size sedans.
- Did you try...

84
00:09:58,369 --> 00:10:02,826
Yes, I reminded them of your remarkable
No.1 Gold Club status in years in the program.

85
00:10:02,912 --> 00:10:05,977
They are literally moving mountains
to see you in a Sebring.

86
00:10:06,063 --> 00:10:09,376
Fair enough. Any other messages?
- Er...your sister Kara called.

87
00:10:09,462 --> 00:10:11,898
Needs to speak urgently
about your sister's wedding.

88
00:10:11,984 --> 00:10:15,036
I told her you were mid-air,
and not even I knew your destination.

89
00:10:15,122 --> 00:10:19,996
Well done. - You got an invitation
to speak at GoalQuest in Vegas.

90
00:10:21,001 --> 00:10:22,082
GoalQuest 20?

91
00:10:22,168 --> 00:10:26,972
<i>Every once in a while, I do speaking engagements,
motivational stuff. But GoalQuest?</i>

92
00:10:27,058 --> 00:10:29,474
<i>We're talking major Tony Robbins shit.</i>

93
00:10:29,560 --> 00:10:34,153
It's got a hologram on it.
They're calling it Dos Equis.

94
00:10:34,239 --> 00:10:36,616
All right, I'll check in.
- I've got Craig Gregory for you.

95
00:10:36,702 --> 00:10:40,211
Wait...ah.
Fuck.

96
00:10:40,297 --> 00:10:42,263
How is my little road warrior?

97
00:10:42,349 --> 00:10:45,144
Hey, 20 minutes from boarding
into a world of bliss.

98
00:10:45,230 --> 00:10:47,534
Real good numbers out of Phoenix,
Ry guy.

99
00:10:47,620 --> 00:10:51,250
You know that Big Auto is about to cut
another 10K by the end of the month?

100
00:10:51,336 --> 00:10:53,426
No kidding.
- Christmas came early.

101
00:10:53,512 --> 00:10:56,980
I wish you could be in five places, but
I need you here in Omaha this week. Alright?

102
00:10:57,066 --> 00:11:01,530
I thought you needed me everywhere.
- We got something real big, a real game changer.

103
00:11:01,616 --> 00:11:03,034
What are we talking about here?

104
00:11:03,120 --> 00:11:09,034
You'll see. Today I took my first crap
in two weeks - hallelujah.

105
00:11:09,120 --> 00:11:13,322
That's me hanging up on you.
- Great, love that sound.

106
00:11:31,682 --> 00:11:34,670
Are you satisfied with Maestro?

107
00:11:37,149 --> 00:11:39,240
Yeah, I am.

108
00:11:39,555 --> 00:11:41,590
A little stingy with their miles.
I like Hertz.

109
00:11:41,676 --> 00:11:47,803
No, Hertz keeps its vehicles too long.
If a car has over 20,000 miles, I won't drive it.

110
00:11:47,901 --> 00:11:50,799
Maestro doesn't instant checkout.
I like the park-and-go.

111
00:11:50,885 --> 00:11:55,453
Hertz doesn't guarantee navigation.
- You don't seem like a girl who needs directions.

112
00:11:55,539 --> 00:12:00,165
I hate asking for directions.
- That's why I get a nav.

113
00:12:01,797 --> 00:12:05,389
That new outfit, Colonial, isn't bad.

114
00:12:06,391 --> 00:12:08,398
Is that a joke?
- Yes.

115
00:12:08,484 --> 00:12:11,884
Their kiosk placement blows.
- They never have available upgrades.

116
00:12:11,970 --> 00:12:15,907
Basically, it's a fleet of shit boxes. I
don't know how they're still in business.

117
00:12:15,993 --> 00:12:19,270
I'm Ryan.
- I'm Alex.

118
00:12:22,377 --> 00:12:27,061
Aww...Maplewood card.
How dare you bring that into this palace?

119
00:12:27,147 --> 00:12:31,060
Hilton offers equal value and better food but
the Maplewood gives out warm cookies at check-in.

120
00:12:31,146 --> 00:12:34,610
I'm a sucker for simulated hospitality.

121
00:12:34,696 --> 00:12:40,973
There's an industry term for that.
It's a mixture of faux and homey - faumey.

122
00:12:41,059 --> 00:12:44,938
Oh, my God.
I wasn't sure this actually existed.

123
00:12:45,024 --> 00:12:50,123
This is the American Airlines...
- It's a Concierge Key, yeah.

124
00:12:53,275 --> 00:12:56,834
What is that, carbon fibre?
- Graphite.

125
00:12:56,931 --> 00:13:00,302
Oh, I love the weight. - I was pretty excited
the day that bad boy came in.

126
00:13:00,388 --> 00:13:06,741
I'll say. I put up pretty pedestrian numbers.
60 thou a year, domestic.

127
00:13:07,056 --> 00:13:09,338
That's not bad.
- Don't patronise me.

128
00:13:09,424 --> 00:13:11,754
What's your total?
