501
00:40:20,091 --> 00:40:22,327
Well, that's a keeper.

502
00:40:22,413 --> 00:40:24,538
Let me see it.

503
00:40:25,169 --> 00:40:29,380
Why she wants reminders of all the
places she hasn't been is beyond me.

504
00:40:29,466 --> 00:40:31,708
I'm sure she'll be crushed
for having missed this airport.

505
00:40:31,794 --> 00:40:36,055
Before Lindbergh crossed the Atlantic,
he took off from that runway.

506
00:40:36,141 --> 00:40:38,064
Wonder why they called it
the Spirit of St Louis?

507
00:40:38,150 --> 00:40:41,034
No.
- Well...

508
00:40:48,229 --> 00:40:51,120
<i>Do you know how fucked
this place is now?</i>

509
00:40:51,206 --> 00:40:53,430
I am the one thing - the one thing-

510
00:40:53,516 --> 00:40:57,672
preventing this place
from being totally fucked in the ass.

511
00:41:03,599 --> 00:41:06,580
Sometimes they just need to vent.

512
00:41:08,653 --> 00:41:12,530
Please, for the love of God,
can I fire the next one?

513
00:41:12,687 --> 00:41:16,722
Miss Barnes, thank you for joining us.
- I'm here to be fired, right?

514
00:41:17,630 --> 00:41:19,772
Well, we're here
to talk about your future.

515
00:41:19,858 --> 00:41:22,325
You don't have to sugar-coat it.
I get the drill.

516
00:41:22,411 --> 00:41:24,935
What are they offering?

517
00:41:25,021 --> 00:41:27,628
Inside the packet, you'll find a clearly
worked out severance package.

518
00:41:27,714 --> 00:41:30,343
Give me the bullet points.

519
00:41:30,534 --> 00:41:31,952
It's actually pretty good -

520
00:41:32,038 --> 00:41:34,400
three months' pay, six months' medical.

521
00:41:34,486 --> 00:41:37,488
And a full year of placement services
through our CTC.

522
00:41:37,574 --> 00:41:41,558
Placement services. That's generous.

523
00:41:43,336 --> 00:41:47,404
Commonly it takes a month of searching
for every $10,000 you expect to earn in salary.

524
00:41:47,490 --> 00:41:50,693
So I could be looking for a while.
- Not necessarily.

525
00:41:50,779 --> 00:41:54,914
Don't even sweat it.
I'm pretty confident about my plans.

526
00:41:55,000 --> 00:41:56,806
Really?
- Yeah.

527
00:41:56,892 --> 00:42:00,174
There's this beautiful bridge
by my house.

528
00:42:00,526 --> 00:42:03,598
I'm gonna go jump off it.

529
00:42:04,539 --> 00:42:06,097
Natalie.

530
00:42:06,183 --> 00:42:07,489
Hey!

531
00:42:07,575 --> 00:42:09,708
Natalie!

532
00:42:18,005 --> 00:42:21,448
People say these things all the time.
It's part of the trade.

533
00:42:21,534 --> 00:42:23,976
They do?
- Yeah.

534
00:42:24,062 --> 00:42:29,505
They say crazy things.
They get worked up.

535
00:42:29,591 --> 00:42:32,241
She was really calm.

536
00:42:32,327 --> 00:42:34,724
I think that's a good sign.

537
00:42:35,007 --> 00:42:39,616
So they don't ever actually do it?
- No. No, it's just talk.

538
00:42:39,702 --> 00:42:44,574
How do you know? Do you follow up?
- No, nothing good's gonna come of that, but..

539
00:42:45,745 --> 00:42:48,532
I wouldn't worry about it.

540
00:42:49,113 --> 00:42:56,022
This is what we do, Natalie. We take people
at their most fragile and we set them adrift.

541
00:42:59,804 --> 00:43:02,420
Ready to go back in?

542
00:43:02,839 --> 00:43:05,724
All right, let's go. Come on.

543
00:43:49,399 --> 00:43:53,355
No, I'm fine. Tell me something sweet.

544
00:43:53,534 --> 00:43:57,770
I'll be back soon. I'm not sure how long
this exercise is supposed to last.

545
00:43:57,856 --> 00:44:01,814
No, I don't even think of him that way.
He's old.

546
00:44:41,705 --> 00:44:45,122
I- I'm done?
- I wasn't expecting this. Not at all.

547
00:44:45,208 --> 00:44:46,212
Just like that?

548
00:44:46,298 --> 00:44:50,080
I'm disappointed that I've given
so much of my life...

549
00:44:50,166 --> 00:44:51,226
This is not fair.

550
00:44:51,312 --> 00:44:53,795
There are people way more qualified
than me now.

551
00:44:53,881 --> 00:44:57,568
I don't know what to do
when I wake up tomorrow.

552
00:45:04,071 --> 00:45:06,332
You OK?

553
00:45:07,591 --> 00:45:10,770
Are we going?
- Yeah.

554
00:45:27,757 --> 00:45:31,280
<i>This is how I start every day of my life.</i>

555
00:45:32,966 --> 00:45:36,289
Now, this is gonna be a little difficult,
so stay with me.

556
00:45:36,375 --> 00:45:38,301
You have a new backpack.

557
00:45:38,387 --> 00:45:42,025
Only this time,
I want you to fill it with people.

558
00:45:42,111 --> 00:45:45,880
Start with casual acquaintances,
friends of friends,

559
00:45:45,966 --> 00:45:47,634
folks around the office.

560
00:45:47,720 --> 00:45:51,102
And then the people you trust
with your most intimate secrets -

561
00:45:51,188 --> 00:45:53,621
your cousins, your aunts, your uncles,

562
00:45:53,707 --> 00:45:57,451
your brothers, your sisters,
your parents,

563
00:45:57,537 --> 00:46:02,990
and finally your husband, your wife,
your boyfriend or your girlfriend.

564
00:46:03,631 --> 00:46:06,632
You get them into that backpack.

565
00:46:07,935 --> 00:46:11,812
Don't worry. I'm not gonna ask you
to light it on fire.

566
00:46:13,097 --> 00:46:15,249
Feel the weight of that bag.

567
00:46:15,335 --> 00:46:21,060
Make no mistake, your relationships are
the heaviest components in your life.

568
00:46:21,535 --> 00:46:26,242
Do you feel the straps
cutting into your shoulders?

569
00:46:26,807 --> 00:46:33,308
All those negotiations and arguments,
and secrets and compromises.

570
00:46:35,831 --> 00:46:38,590
<i>You don't need to carry all that weight.</i>

571
00:46:39,028 --> 00:46:41,877
<i>Why don't you set that bag down?</i>

572
00:46:43,439 --> 00:46:49,337
Some animals were meant to carry each other,
to live symbiotically for a lifetime -

573
00:46:49,423 --> 00:46:54,740
star-crossed lovers, monogamous swans.
We are not those animals.

574
00:46:56,487 --> 00:46:58,716
The slower we move, the faster we die.

575
00:46:58,802 --> 00:47:02,496
We are not swans.

576
00:47:03,087 --> 00:47:05,471
We're sharks.

577
00:47:18,831 --> 00:47:20,743
<i>Never?
- No.</i>

578
00:47:20,829 --> 00:47:22,933
Ever?
- No.

579
00:47:23,019 --> 00:47:25,390
You never want to get married?
- Nope.

580
00:47:25,476 --> 00:47:27,520
Never want kids?
- Not a chance.

581
00:47:27,606 --> 00:47:30,284
Ever?
- Never.

582
00:47:30,370 --> 00:47:33,709
Is that so bizarre?
- Yes.

583
00:47:33,795 --> 00:47:38,063
Yes, it is.
- I just don't see the value in it.

584
00:47:38,477 --> 00:47:41,104
Right, sell it to me.
- What?

585
00:47:41,190 --> 00:47:43,450
Sell me marriage.

586
00:47:44,741 --> 00:47:48,248
OK, how about love?
- OK.

587
00:47:48,551 --> 00:47:53,146
Stability, just somebody you can count on...
- How many stable marriages do you know?

588
00:47:53,232 --> 00:47:56,506
Somebody to talk to,
someone to spend your life with.

589
00:47:56,592 --> 00:48:00,292
I'm surrounded by people to talk to.
That won't change.

590
00:48:01,003 --> 00:48:03,832
How about just not dying alone?

591
00:48:04,275 --> 00:48:08,306
Starting when I was 12, we moved each
of my grandparents to a nursing facility.

592
00:48:08,392 --> 00:48:12,960
My parents went the same way.
Make no mistake, we all die alone.

593
00:48:13,046 --> 00:48:17,842
Now, those cult members in San Diego,
with the Kool-Aid and the sneakers...

594
00:48:17,928 --> 00:48:20,059
they didn't die alone.

595
00:48:20,145 --> 00:48:22,806
I'm just saying there are options.

596
00:48:25,577 --> 00:48:27,938
Oh, fuck.

597
00:48:28,569 --> 00:48:31,270
Brian left me.

598
00:48:37,191 --> 00:48:39,628
All right.

599
00:48:41,443 --> 00:48:44,320
OK. Ok. All right.

600
00:48:45,557 --> 00:48:48,898
All right. Shh, shh.

601
00:49:01,562 --> 00:49:05,704
Natalie, this is Alex, my friend.
This is Natalie.

602
00:49:06,157 --> 00:49:08,461
I should give you both a moment.

603
00:49:08,547 --> 00:49:13,864
No. No, that's fine.
I'm fine. It's a pleasure to meet you.

604
00:49:14,161 --> 00:49:18,308
Maybe we should just all
go up to our rooms and freshen up.

605
00:49:18,394 --> 00:49:20,778
Maybe a drink?
- Now you're talking.

606
00:49:20,864 --> 00:49:23,598
<i>Brian: I think it's time we C othter people</i>

607
00:49:24,248 --> 00:49:26,576
He broke up with you
with a text message?

608
00:49:26,662 --> 00:49:30,128
Kind of like firing someone
over the internet.

609
00:49:31,635 --> 00:49:35,204
What a weaselly prick.
- But what does that make me?

610
00:49:35,327 --> 00:49:37,725
Someone who falls for a prick.
- We all fall for them.

611
00:49:37,811 --> 00:49:40,620
Pricks are
spontaneous, unpredictable and fun.

612
00:49:40,706 --> 00:49:43,698
Then we're surprised
when they turn out to be pricks.

613
00:49:44,069 --> 00:49:48,150
I followed him to Omaha.
- You did?

614
00:49:48,323 --> 00:49:52,868
I had a job waiting for me in San Francisco
when he got an offer from ConAgra.

615
00:49:53,647 --> 00:49:56,404
He said we could start a life together.

616
00:49:56,963 --> 00:50:00,728
So I followed him.
- To Nebraska?

617
00:50:02,837 --> 00:50:06,074
I thought I'd be engaged by now.

618
00:50:06,315 --> 00:50:07,766
No offence.

619
00:50:07,852 --> 00:50:10,096
None taken.
- That's all right.

620
00:50:11,348 --> 00:50:14,894
When I was 16,
I thought by 23 I'd be married,

621
00:50:14,980 --> 00:50:19,609
maybe have a kid, corner office by day,
entertaining at night.

622
00:50:19,695 --> 00:50:21,866
I was supposed to be driving
a Grand Cherokee by now.

623
00:50:21,952 --> 00:50:25,009
Life can underwhelm you that way.

624
00:50:25,095 --> 00:50:28,396
I mean, where did you
think you'd be by um...

625
00:50:30,691 --> 00:50:34,514
It doesn't work that way.
- At a certain point, you stop with the deadlines.

626
00:50:34,600 --> 00:50:36,061
It can be counterproductive.

627
00:50:36,147 --> 00:50:38,128
I don't want to say anything
anti-feminist.

628
00:50:38,214 --> 00:50:41,561
I really appreciate
all your generation did for me.

629
00:50:41,647 --> 00:50:43,454
It was our pleasure.
- Well done.

630
00:50:43,540 --> 00:50:46,366
But sometimes it feels like,
no matter how much success I have,

631
00:50:46,452 --> 00:50:49,464
it's not gonna matter
until I find the right guy.

632
00:50:50,021 --> 00:50:52,657
You really thought
this guy was the one?

633
00:50:52,743 --> 00:50:55,106
I could have made it work.

634
00:50:55,192 --> 00:50:58,254
He um... He really fit the bill.

635
00:50:58,340 --> 00:51:00,630
You know?
- The bill?

636
00:51:00,716 --> 00:51:03,199
White collar, college grad.

637
00:51:03,285 --> 00:51:07,390
Loves dogs, likes funny movies.
Six-foot-one, brown hair, kind eyes,

638
00:51:07,476 --> 00:51:12,984
works in finance but is outdoorsy...
you know, on the weekends.

639
00:51:13,271 --> 00:51:19,172
I always imagined he'd have a single
syllable name like Matt or John...

640
00:51:19,257 --> 00:51:21,222
or Dave.

641
00:51:21,383 --> 00:51:24,262
In a perfect world, he drives a 4Runner, and

642
00:51:24,348 --> 00:51:27,348
and the only thing he loves
more than me is his golden lab.

643
00:51:27,888 --> 00:51:30,662
And a nice smile.

644
00:51:32,867 --> 00:51:36,904
What about you?
- Let me think.

645
00:51:38,397 --> 00:51:43,205
Honestly, by the time you're 34, all the
physical requirements go out the window.

646
00:51:43,291 --> 00:51:47,044
Like you secretly pray
that he'll be taller than you.

647
00:51:47,943 --> 00:51:52,400
Not an asshole would be nice. Someone who
enjoys my company, comes from a good family.

648
00:51:52,486 --> 00:51:54,612
You don't think about that
when you're younger.

649
00:51:54,698 --> 00:51:58,818
I don't know...
someone who wants kids.

650
00:51:58,904 --> 00:52:01,919
Likes kids. Wants kids

651
00:52:02,005 --> 00:52:05,962
Healthy enough to play with his kids.

652
00:52:07,757 --> 00:52:11,113
Please let him earn more money
than I do.

653
00:52:11,199 --> 00:52:14,274
You might not understand that now,
but believe me, you will one day.

654
00:52:14,360 --> 00:52:17,530
Otherwise that's a recipe for disaster.

655
00:52:18,981 --> 00:52:21,603
And hopefully some hair on his head.

656
00:52:21,689 --> 00:52:25,504
But I mean even that's not
a deal breaker these days.

657
00:52:28,663 --> 00:52:31,010
A nice smile.

658
00:52:32,301 --> 00:52:36,418
Yeah, a nice smile.
Nice smile just might do it.

659
00:52:38,739 --> 00:52:41,134
Wow, that was depressing.

660
00:52:42,385 --> 00:52:45,624
I should just date women.
- Tried it.

661
00:52:45,801 --> 00:52:48,438
We're no picnic ourselves.

662
00:52:51,313 --> 00:52:54,464
I don't mind being married
to my career.

663
00:52:55,180 --> 00:52:58,388
And I don't expect it to hold me in bed
as I fall asleep.

664
00:53:02,439 --> 00:53:05,207
I just don't want to settle.

665
00:53:05,293 --> 00:53:09,266
You're young. Right now you see
settling as some sort of a failure.

666
00:53:09,352 --> 00:53:13,095
It is...by definition.

667
00:53:13,181 --> 00:53:17,147
But by the time someone is right
for you, it won't feel like settling.

668
00:53:17,233 --> 00:53:18,744
And the only person left to judge you

669
00:53:18,830 --> 00:53:22,354
will be the 23-year-old girl
with a target on your back.

670
00:53:25,996 --> 00:53:28,706
So what's the plan for the evening?

671
00:53:29,029 --> 00:53:33,400
Well, we were gonna hit that party
for the tech conference at the hotel.

672
00:53:33,486 --> 00:53:37,206
I didn't know you could just attend
those. I thought you had to register.

673
00:53:37,292 --> 00:53:40,070
Technically,
I don't think it's open to the public.

674
00:53:40,156 --> 00:53:44,582
Stop by.
- You're gonna crash it?

675
00:53:47,538 --> 00:53:52,809
have a good time, usually.
- No, no, I get it. I'm in.

676
00:54:12,507 --> 00:54:14,811
Jennifer Chu?

677
00:54:14,897 --> 00:54:17,931
Shit!
- Ah, it'll be fine.

678
00:54:39,493 --> 00:54:41,991
Doing all right?

679
00:54:42,956 --> 00:54:46,073
Yeah. This was a great idea.

680
00:54:47,292 --> 00:54:49,765
You're so pretty.

681
00:54:50,048 --> 00:54:53,670
You're exactly
what I wanna look like in 15 years.

682
00:54:53,945 --> 00:54:57,555
Thank you, Natalie.
- You should dance.

683
00:55:01,033 --> 00:55:02,168
Come on.
- No, no, no.

684
00:55:02,254 --> 00:55:05,002
Come on.
- Oh!

685
00:55:21,403 --> 00:55:24,856
I'm Dave.
- I'm Natalie.

686
00:55:25,043 --> 00:55:27,424
Who's Jennifer?

687
00:55:28,240 --> 00:55:30,798
I don't know.

688
