01:16:40,493 --> 01:16:43,842
Jim seems like a good guy.
- Yeah, isn't he great?

922
01:16:43,928 --> 01:16:46,938
He's going to make a great husband.

923
01:16:48,220 --> 01:16:54,146
You know, Julie, I was thinking,
you know, with Dad not being here, erm...

924
01:16:54,463 --> 01:16:58,332
I was wondering if you had anybody
to walk you down the aisle.

925
01:17:03,251 --> 01:17:07,922
No, Jim's uncle is gonna do it.
- He's been really supportive.

926
01:17:08,008 --> 01:17:09,644
He's been great.

927
01:17:09,730 --> 01:17:13,758
Well, good. That's great.
I just wanted to make sure that you...

928
01:17:14,089 --> 01:17:17,342
I wanted you to be covered, that's all.

929
01:17:20,037 --> 01:17:22,300
So, I should be there, what?

930
01:17:22,386 --> 01:17:28,460
The other guests are arriving around
five and things get going at five-thirty so...

931
01:17:28,546 --> 01:17:31,455
around then.
- OK.

932
01:17:33,075 --> 01:17:36,975
Oh. Let me...
I'm gonna help you with those.

933
01:17:38,059 --> 01:17:40,252
Got it.

934
01:17:40,447 --> 01:17:44,891
It's OK. It's OK, it's OK.

935
01:17:52,735 --> 01:17:54,921
None of that was here.

936
01:17:55,007 --> 01:17:57,776
This is all new.

937
01:18:08,034 --> 01:18:10,004
Really?

938
01:18:10,359 --> 01:18:14,051
Is that all you got?
- What?

939
01:18:20,476 --> 01:18:22,970
Give me a boost.

940
01:18:24,001 --> 01:18:26,165
Watch...

941
01:18:26,384 --> 01:18:28,838
Hang on.

942
01:18:35,227 --> 01:18:37,832
I took Geography in here.

943
01:18:38,007 --> 01:18:40,353
You ever fool around
with one of your teachers?

944
01:18:40,439 --> 01:18:44,924
No. Did you?
- No. Not until college.

945
01:18:49,297 --> 01:18:52,086
That's me on the right.

946
01:18:53,218 --> 01:18:57,786
It's kinda hard to tell.
- You can tell by the eyebrows.

947
01:18:57,997 --> 01:19:02,230
You played basketball?
- I was a point guard. Don't act so surprised.

948
01:19:02,316 --> 01:19:05,777
I didn't know you were such a jock.

949
01:19:05,863 --> 01:19:08,107
That's me too.

950
01:19:08,193 --> 01:19:11,150
And that.

951
01:19:12,641 --> 01:19:14,964
My first fight.
- How'd it go?

952
01:19:15,050 --> 01:19:17,509
Got my ass kicked.

953
01:19:17,595 --> 01:19:26,034
This is where we used to go to make out.
- Oh, yes. Yeah. This is very romantic.

954
01:19:37,949 --> 01:19:42,458
I'm really happy I came here.
- So am I.

955
01:19:48,072 --> 01:19:50,358
It's Kara.

956
01:19:51,293 --> 01:19:54,063
Ryan, where are you?
We're having a meltdown here.

957
01:19:54,149 --> 01:19:55,246
What's going on? What happened?

958
01:19:55,332 --> 01:19:57,604
It's Jim. Can you get back here?
We need your help.

959
01:19:57,690 --> 01:20:00,036
OK.

960
01:20:00,806 --> 01:20:03,118
We gotta go.

961
01:20:05,831 --> 01:20:09,412
I'll grab your suit.
- Thanks.

962
01:20:27,548 --> 01:20:30,258
What happened?
- Jim's got cold feet.

963
01:20:30,344 --> 01:20:32,995
Today?
- Yeah, that's how cold feet work.

964
01:20:33,081 --> 01:20:36,122
What do you want me to do?
- Talk to him.

965
01:20:36,208 --> 01:20:39,100
You want me to talk to him?
- Hey, it's either you or me.

966
01:20:39,186 --> 01:20:41,670
You know my track record.
I've already struck out once.

967
01:20:41,756 --> 01:20:44,268
I haven't been to bat.
I haven't been in the dugout.

968
01:20:44,354 --> 01:20:47,006
Don't you talk for a living?
Motivational-type stuff?

969
01:20:47,092 --> 01:20:49,715
I tell people how to avoid commitment.

970
01:20:49,801 --> 01:20:53,020
It's a philosophy.
- It's stupid.

971
01:20:53,106 --> 01:20:56,250
Hey, it could have helped you.
- Ryan.

972
01:20:56,336 --> 01:21:01,604
You haven't been around much.
Fuck - basically, you don't exist to us.

973
01:21:01,690 --> 01:21:04,523
I know you wanna be there for her.

974
01:21:04,609 --> 01:21:09,015
Well, here it is. This is your chance.

975
01:21:29,467 --> 01:21:32,280
Hey. What's up, Ryan?

976
01:21:33,407 --> 01:21:36,739
Jim.
- You ever read this before?

977
01:21:37,006 --> 01:21:41,768
Yeah, it's pretty powerful stuff.
- I'll say.

978
01:21:44,117 --> 01:21:49,985
Er...Kara mentioned that you were
having some thoughts.

979
01:21:50,132 --> 01:21:54,923
I don't think I'm going to be able to er...
to do this.

980
01:21:55,151 --> 01:21:58,916
Why would you say that...today?

981
01:21:59,221 --> 01:22:03,288
Well, last night I was kinda laying
in bed and I couldn't get to sleep.

982
01:22:03,374 --> 01:22:06,697
So I started thinking about the wedding
and the ceremony,

983
01:22:06,783 --> 01:22:10,171
and about our buying a house
and moving in together.

984
01:22:10,257 --> 01:22:14,090
And having a kid,
and having another kid and then

985
01:22:14,446 --> 01:22:16,758
Christmas and Thanksgiving
and spring break.

986
01:22:16,844 --> 01:22:20,318
Going to football games, and then
all of a sudden they're graduating.

987
01:22:20,404 --> 01:22:24,440
They're getting jobs, getting married.
And, you know, I'm a grandparent.

988
01:22:24,526 --> 01:22:27,847
And then I'm retired.
I'm losing my hair, I'm getting fat.

989
01:22:27,933 --> 01:22:30,403
And then the next thing you know
I'm dead.

990
01:22:30,489 --> 01:22:35,088
I'm just, like...I can't stop from thinking,
what's the point?

991
01:22:37,555 --> 01:22:40,608
I mean, what is the point?

992
01:22:40,697 --> 01:22:45,678
The point?
- What am I starting here?

993
01:22:46,573 --> 01:22:50,027
Jim, it's...marriage.

994
01:22:50,290 --> 01:22:54,756
It's one of the most beautiful things on earth.
It's what people aspire to.

995
01:22:54,842 --> 01:22:57,740
You never got married.
- That's true.

996
01:22:57,826 --> 01:23:02,127
I mean, you never even tried.
- Well, it's hard to define try.

997
01:23:02,213 --> 01:23:06,687
I don't know, just you seem happier
than all my married friends.

998
01:23:08,271 --> 01:23:12,086
Look, Jim, I'm not going to lie to you.
Marriage can be a pain in the ass.

999
01:23:12,172 --> 01:23:16,955
And you're right. This all is just stuff
that leads to your eventual demise.

1000
01:23:17,041 --> 01:23:19,097
Yes.
- And we're all on running clocks.

1001
01:23:19,183 --> 01:23:22,525
And they can't be slowed down
or paused.

1002
01:23:23,504 --> 01:23:26,965
And...we all end up in the same place.
- yeah.

1003
01:23:28,291 --> 01:23:33,116
There is no point.
- There is no point. That's what I'm saying.

1004
01:23:37,447 --> 01:23:40,100
You know, er...

1005
01:23:40,497 --> 01:23:44,758
I'm not normally the guy
you would talk to about stuff like this.

1006
01:23:47,671 --> 01:23:50,336
If you think about it...

1007
01:23:51,518 --> 01:23:55,471
your favourite memories, the most
important moments in your life.

1008
01:23:55,762 --> 01:23:57,832
Were you alone?

1009
01:23:58,195 --> 01:24:02,047
No, I guess not.

1010
01:24:02,374 --> 01:24:04,412
Come to think of it,

1011
01:24:04,498 --> 01:24:07,705
last night, the night before your wedding
when all this shit is swirling around in your head,

1012
01:24:07,791 --> 01:24:10,233
weren't you guys in separate bedrooms?

1013
01:24:10,319 --> 01:24:15,651
Yeah, Julie went back to the apartment and
I was just by myself in the honeymoon suite.

1014
01:24:15,737 --> 01:24:19,545
Kinda lonely, huh?
- Yes, it was pretty lonely.

1015
01:24:20,617 --> 01:24:23,541
Life's better with company.

1016
01:24:24,441 --> 01:24:28,798
Yeah...
- Everybody needs a co-pilot.

1017
01:24:30,059 --> 01:24:33,336
That was a nice touch.
- Thanks.

1018
01:24:35,415 --> 01:24:40,265
So er... what's the mood like out there?
- It's not good.

1019
01:24:40,351 --> 01:24:44,176
She's pretty pissed?
- Just upset.

1020
01:24:45,418 --> 01:24:48,100
What should I do?

1021
01:24:49,455 --> 01:24:51,748
Go get her.

1022
01:25:05,443 --> 01:25:08,997
I'm such a fuck-up.
I love you so much.

1023
01:25:09,083 --> 01:25:12,205
Will you be my co-pilot?

1024
01:25:13,303 --> 01:25:16,825
Yes. Yes.

1025
01:25:21,004 --> 01:25:23,681
Welcome home.

1026
01:27:57,902 --> 01:28:01,915
OK, this is your stop.

1027
01:28:08,050 --> 01:28:12,783
When am I gonna see you?
- You're just gonna have to come visit.

1028
01:28:12,888 --> 01:28:15,685
Oh...so settled.

1029
01:28:16,256 --> 01:28:23,077
You're not gonna change on me, are you?
- No. Same guy. Just one address.

1030
01:28:23,642 --> 01:28:29,103
<i>This is your final boarding
call for Flight 3972 to Chicago.</i>

1031
01:28:30,002 --> 01:28:33,768
Right. Call me when you get lonely.

1032
01:28:36,054 --> 01:28:38,471
I'm lonely.

1033
01:29:10,919 --> 01:29:12,961
Some guy sits in a conference room somewhere

1034
01:29:13,047 --> 01:29:16,328
and our server routes his session
to one of our termination engineers.

1035
01:29:16,414 --> 01:29:18,021
"Termination engineers"? Really?

1036
01:29:18,107 --> 01:29:20,755
I preferred "terminators"
but it bumped with Legal.

1037
01:29:20,841 --> 01:29:22,225
Can't imagine why.

1038
01:29:22,311 --> 01:29:26,246
The workflow takes them through anything
from a standard dismissal to a violent aggressor.

1039
01:29:26,332 --> 01:29:28,476
What are they doing now, practising?

1040
01:29:28,562 --> 01:29:33,103
Beta testing, role-playing.
We go live at the end of the month.

1041
01:29:33,270 --> 01:29:35,581
Kyle, you're running through the events
too quickly.

1042
01:29:35,667 --> 01:29:39,511
Give them time to acknowledge
each statement. It's a legal thing.

1043
01:29:40,040 --> 01:29:43,759
Ryan?
- Mm? Oh. Yeah. There's more?

1044
01:29:50,078 --> 01:29:51,333
This is ridiculous.

1045
01:29:51,419 --> 01:29:56,605
<i>Legal's starting to come hard
at me on this term "terminate"...</i>

1046
01:30:22,354 --> 01:30:25,823
<i>Life to the power of you!</i>

1047
01:30:35,074 --> 01:30:38,212
<i>Ladies and gentlemen. Put your hands
together for today's challenge speaker,</i>

1048
01:30:38,298 --> 01:30:41,260
<i>Mr Ryan Bingham</i>

1049
01:30:42,060 --> 01:30:44,217
Go get 'em.

1050
01:30:54,091 --> 01:30:58,567
Last year I flew 350,000 miles.

1051
01:30:58,747 --> 01:31:01,360
The moon is 250.

1052
01:31:03,861 --> 01:31:08,240
I want you to imagine for a second
that you're carrying a backpack.

1053
01:31:08,326 --> 01:31:11,465
I want you to feel the straps
on your shoulders

1054
01:31:12,072 --> 01:31:14,192
You feel 'em?

1055
01:31:15,145 --> 01:31:20,638
Now I want you to pack it with
all the stuff that you have in your life.

1056
01:31:21,017 --> 01:31:27,695
Start with the little things -
the things on shelves and in drawers.

1057
01:31:46,070 --> 01:31:48,708
Excuse me.

1058
01:31:51,499 --> 01:31:53,582
What the fuck are you doing?

1059
01:31:53,668 --> 01:31:58,622
<i>Relax. We'll have
your next guest out in one sec.</i>

1060
01:32:20,341 --> 01:32:23,382
Hey, you gotta sign.
- OK.

1061
01:32:24,391 --> 01:32:26,814
OK, thank you.

1062
01:32:29,171 --> 01:32:33,320
Hey, you forgot to give me
your Hertz No.1 Gold Card!

1063
01:33:08,076 --> 01:33:10,785
So I was in the neighbourhood.

1064
01:33:25,444 --> 01:33:30,379
<i>Hey, honey, who's at the door?
- Just somebody who's lost.</i>

1065
01:34:27,998 --> 01:34:29,198
Alex?

1066
01:34:29,284 --> 01:34:32,211
What were you thinking,
showing up at my door like that?

1067
01:34:32,297 --> 01:34:36,156
What do you mean? I wanted to see you.
I didn't know you had a family.

1068
01:34:36,242 --> 01:34:37,957
Why didn't you tell me that?

1069
01:34:38,043 --> 01:34:41,880
Sorry I ruined your evening but you
could have screwed things up for me.

1070
01:34:41,966 --> 01:34:46,533
That's my family. That's my real life.

1071
01:34:48,111 --> 01:34:51,628
I thought I was a part of your real life.

1072
01:34:52,002 --> 01:34:55,126
I thought we signed up
for the same thing.

1073
01:34:56,255 --> 01:35:01,061
Try and help me understand exactly
what it is that you signed up for.

1074
01:35:01,496 --> 01:35:06,129
I thought our relationship
was perfectly clear. I mean...

1075
01:35:06,215 --> 01:35:09,586
you are an escape.

1076
01:35:10,869 --> 01:35:13,602
<i>You're a break from our normal lives,
you're a...</i>

1077
01:35:13,688 --> 01:35:16,748
a parenthesis.

1078
01:35:18,955 --> 01:35:20,677
I'm a parenthesis?

1079
01:35:20,763 --> 01:35:25,128
I mean...
what do you want?

1080
01:35:26,211 --> 01:35:28,768
Tell me what you want.

1081
01:35:32,865 --> 01:35:35,616
You don't even know what you want.

1082
01:35:35,702 --> 01:35:40,107
<i>Ryan, I'm a grown-up, OK?</i>

1083
01:35:40,193 --> 01:35:45,580
So if you would like to see me again,
then then give me a call.

1084
01:35:46,529 --> 01:35:48,807
OK?

1085
01:36:03,826 --> 01:36:06,810
<i>Ladies and gentlemen, we
have a special announcement to make.</i>

1086
01:36:06,896 --> 01:36:11,266
Our pilot has just informed me that we
are passing over the city of Dubuque,

1087
01:36:11,352 --> 01:36:16,792
which might not mean much to most of you,
but means a lot to one of our flyers today.

1088
01:36:16,878 --> 01:36:22,907
Oh, no.
- He just hit 10 million miles!

1089
01:36:25,591 --> 01:36:28,627
Congratulations.
- Such an amazing accomplishment.

1090
01:36:28,713 --> 01:36:31,443
You must be very excited.

1091
01:36:31,529 --> 01:36:33,940
Hi, Captain.
- Captain.

1092
01:36:34,026 --> 01:36:36,345
That seat taken?

1093
01:36:36,431 --> 01:36:38,969
No. No.

1094
01:36:44,975 --> 01:36:48,338
You're the youngest yet to hit 10 mil.

1095
01:36:48,424 --> 01:36:51,418
Don't know where you found the time.

1096
01:36:51,504 --> 01:36:54,988
Yeah.
I don't know.

1097
01:37:00,006 --> 01:37:02,156
Here you go.

1098
01:37:03,636 --> 01:37:06,589
Seventh card we've made.

1099
01:37:06,803 --> 01:37:09,296
Small club.

1100
01:37:10,895 --> 01:37:14,700
We really appreciate your loyalty.

1101
01:37:16,800 --> 01:37:20,130
You know how many times
I thought about this moment?

1102
01:37:22,033 --> 01:37:25,481
Played out the conversation
that you and I would have right here.

1103
01:37:25,567 --> 01:37:27,748
Really?

1104
01:37:29,791 --> 01:37:32,692
What did you want to say?

1105
01:37:36,892 --> 01:37:39,529
You know, I don't remember.

1106
01:37:41,051 --> 01:37:45,777
That's all right.
It happens to all of us.

1107
01:37:48,752 --> 01:37:51,326
So where are you from?

1108
01:37:56,873 --> 01:37:59,343
I'm from here.

1109
01:38:17,051 --> 01:38:19,380
<i>Hello, Mr Bingham.</i>

1110
01:38:20,040 --> 01:38:21,571
How did you know it was me?

1111
01:38:21,657 --> 01:38:26,437
<i>This is your dedicated line. We reserve them
for our most loyal and appreciated flyers.</i>

1112
01:38:26,523 --> 01:38:32,076
I'd like to transfer some of my miles.
Can I open up an account to Jim and Julie Miller?

1113
01:38:32,162 --> 01:38:34,928
<i>Certainly. How many miles
would you like to transfer?</i>

1114
01:38:35,014 --> 01:38:37,305
How many miles does it take
to circle the globe?

1115
01:38:37,391 --> 01:38:41,667
<i>We have our round-the-world tickets.
They're 500,000 miles each.</i>

1116
01:38:41,753 --> 01:38:43,396
That'd be fine.
- Got a second?

1117
01:38:43,482 --> 01:38:44,932
I'll call you back.

1118
01:38:45,018 --> 01:38:47,587
What happened to you yesterday?
I was trying to get hold of you.

1119
01:38:47,673 --> 01:38:51,506
I was some personal stuff.
What's going on?

1120
01:38:51,592 --> 01:38:54,037
Do you remember Karen Barnes,

1121
01:38:54,710 --> 01:38:57,895
part of a 30-person reduction
a few weeks back in Wichita?

1122
01:38:57,981 --> 01:39:03,042
Natalie fired her.
- Fired dozens of people a day. I...

1123
01:39:03,128 --> 01:39:06,193
She killed herself - jumped off a bridge.

1124
01:39:07,795 --> 01:39:09,224
Fuck.

1125
01:39:09,310 --> 01:39:13,632
I need to know if you remember
any woman that gave you any signals,

1126
01:39:13,718 --> 01:39:16,844
depression...
- They're all depressed. We're firing them.

1127
01:39:16,930 --> 01:39:22,308
Hey, I need to ask you this stuff, OK?
- No, I don't remember anything.

1128
01:39:22,687 --> 01:39:25,858
You never think that they're...

1129
01:39:26,423 --> 01:39:28,282
You don't remember any woman
that gave you any signals?

1130
01:39:28,368 --> 01:39:32,684
Anything at all, Ryan?
- No, nothing stands out.

1131
01:39:35,293 --> 01:39:39,242
Is Natalie all right?
- Natalie quit.

1132
01:39:42,224 --> 01:39:46,138
She quit?
- Text message.

1133
01:39:46,581 --> 01:39:50,259
Fucking nice, right?
No-one's got any manners any more.

1134
01:39:50,345 --> 01:39:55,312
Did she say where she was going?
- No. She was a little upset.

1135
01:39:56,556 --> 01:39:59,154
I should give her a call.

1136
01:40:01,867 --> 01:40:04,936
I need you back in the air.

1137
01:40:07,609 --> 01:40:10,779
Hey. Did you hear what I said?
I thought you'd be thrilled about that.

1138
01:40:10,865 --> 01:40:13,841
It's fine. What about
the videoconferencing?

1139
01:40:13,927 --> 01:40:20,048
CTC is going to pause the new media front.
They're gonna give it some more thought.

1140
01:40:20,134 --> 01:40:24,678
We are gonna get our workhorses back
in the air doing what they do best, OK?

1141
01:40:25,876 --> 01:40:28,168
How long are you sending me out?

1142
01:40:28,254 --> 01:40:33,395
We're gonna let you sail and sail.
You send us a postcard if you ever get there.

1143
01:40:47,042 --> 01:40:49,670
So what happened?

1144
01:40:50,653 --> 01:40:52,924
How exactly do you mean?

1145
01:40:53,010 --> 01:40:55,276
You graduated top of your class.

1146
01:40:55,362 --> 01:40:58,044
You seemed to have your pick of
employment, including here.

1147
01:40:58,130 --> 01:41:02,902
Instead you went to Omaha
to fire people for a living?

1148
01:41:04,281 --> 01:41:07,164
It's challenging work.
- I'll say!

1149
01:41:07,250 --> 01:41:10,203
I can't imagine doing that,
day in, day out.

1150
01:41:10,289 --> 01:41:12,582
Not in this climate.

1151
01:41:14,077 --> 01:41:16,874
I followed a boy.

1152
01:41:20,523 --> 01:41:23,792
I guess everybody does that
at one point or another.

1153
01:41:29,241 --> 01:41:31,657
This guy says I'd be lucky to have you.

1154
01:41:31,743 --> 01:41:33,975
<i>To whom it may concern.</i>

1155
01:41:34,061 --> 01:41:37,129
<i>I can't even count the number
of people I've fired in my lifetime.</i>

1156
01:41:37,215 --> 01:41:40,823
<i>So many that I've actually forgotten
what it's like to hire somebody.</i>

1157
01:41:40,909 --> 01:41:45,925
<i>We've never met, but I know you'd
be lucky to have Natalie Keener.</i>

1158
01:41:46,011 --> 01:41:48,851
<i>My advice?
Take her and don't look back.</i>

1159
01:41:48,937 --> 01:41:52,627
<i>She'll be the best decision
you've made in a long time.</i>

1160
01:41:56,230 --> 01:41:59,091
I sure hope he's right.

1161
01:42:09,997 --> 01:42:11,920
<i>Well, I don't have a lot of hope,</i>

1162
01:42:12,006 --> 01:42:14,624
<i>and I really don't know
when it's gonna get better.</i>

1163
01:42:14,710 --> 01:42:17,354
There's a lot of people unemployed.

1164
01:42:17,440 --> 01:42:22,637
And I really don't know when there's
gonna be light at the end of the tunnel.

1165
01:42:22,723 --> 01:42:24,387
I can't find much to talk about.

1166
01:42:24,473 --> 01:42:27,323
Talk about being proud.
I'm proud of my kids.

1167
01:42:27,409 --> 01:42:32,533
I think the anger comes from the fact
that I just wasn't needed any more.

1168
01:42:32,619 --> 01:42:34,782
I would say, you know, uh...

1169
01:42:34,868 --> 01:42:37,592
without my friends and my family,

1170
01:42:37,678 --> 01:42:39,492
I wouldn't have made it.

1171
01:42:39,578 --> 01:42:42,388
It would have been a lot tougher
if I'd had to make it on my own.

1172
01:42:42,474 --> 01:42:46,721
When I wake up in the morning
and I look over and I see my wife,

1173
01:42:46,807 --> 01:42:49,723
that gives me the sense of purpose.

1174
01:42:49,809 --> 01:42:52,695
It's not all about the money.
Money can keep you warm.

1175
01:42:52,781 --> 01:42:57,136
It pays your heating bills.
It can buy you a blanket.

1176
01:42:58,004 --> 01:43:02,355
But it doesn't keep you as warm
as when my husband holds me.

1177
01:43:02,441 --> 01:43:07,192
Let me get up. Let me get out.
Let me find something.

1178
01:43:07,565 --> 01:43:12,524
So my kids are my purpose.
My family.

1179
01:43:41,193 --> 01:43:46,380
<i>Tonight most people will be welcomed
home by jumping dogs and squealing kids.</i>

1180
01:43:46,856 --> 01:43:51,213
<i>Their spouses will ask about their day
and tonight they'll sleep.</i>

1181
01:43:51,765 --> 01:43:56,450
<i>The stars will wheel forth
from their daytime hiding places.</i>

1182
01:43:57,269 --> 01:44:00,476
<i>And one of those lights,
slightly brighter than the rest,</i>

1183
01:44:00,727 --> 01:44:04,692
<i>will be my wing tip passing over.</i>

